#### **Day 63: Input Validation (Hibernate Validator)**
```markdown
# Day 63: Validating DTOs

**Topics Covered:**
1. Adding `spring-boot-starter-validation`.
2. Validation Annotations: `@NotNull`, `@Size`, `@Email`, `@Min`.
3. The `@Valid` annotation in Controller.
4. Preventing bad data from entering the logic.

**Learning Summary:**
We shouldn't trust user input. Today I learned how to validate data automatically using annotations instead of writing huge `if-else` blocks. I applied validation rules on my DTO fields. If the input is invalid, Spring Boot automatically rejects the request before it even reaches the method logic.

**Code Snippet:**
```java
// DTO Class
public class UserDTO {
    
    @NotNull(message = "Username cannot be null")
    @Size(min = 3, message = "Username must be at least 3 chars")
    private String username;

    @Email(message = "Invalid Email format")
    private String email;
    
    @Min(value = 18, message = "Age must be 18+")
    private int age;
}

// Controller
@PostMapping
public String register(@Valid @RequestBody UserDTO user) {
    return "Validation Passed. Registering user...";
}
